R Notebook

There is a baseR way of dealing with timeseries, dealing with objects of ts class.

There are a range of packages in the tidyverse which deal with time series in a tidy format

library(lubridate)

package lubridate was built under R version 3.6.2
Attaching package: lubridate

The following object is masked from package:tsibble:

    interval

The following objects are masked from package:base:

    date, intersect, setdiff, union

Tsibble

tsibble is a tibble for time series data

Half hourly record of electricity demand in Victoria, Australia

tsibbles can have an index, which is either timedate or date or time find index variable

index_var(vic_elec)

[1] "Time"

tsibbles can have a key,

We can use tidyverse syntax on tsibble

Additional functions in tsibbles

Filter index

vic_elec %>% 
  filter_index("2012-01")

System time zone: "Europe/London".
It may yield an unexpected output. Please see `?filter_index` for details.

Add year column to tsibble

vic_elec <- vic_elec %>% 
  mutate(year = lubridate::year(Time))

Group by are more complicated because we have to preserve the index

Plotting time series

Often needs a group and summarise first as too much data will build an unreadable plot.

Rolling window statistics

A different way of summarising/aggregating data Window of 10: calculate for 1:10, 2:11, 3:12, 4:13, 5:14. Gives us a similar number of values to what we started with, but smoothes out fluctuations - helps us to see trend. We also have cumulative mean.

A moving average using a window of 2000

Plot moving average

Task - moving average with window size of 200 More impacted by daily trends

vic_elec <- vic_elec %>% 
  mutate(
    temp_moving_avg_200 = slide_dbl(
      Temperature,
      # functional notation, with . standing for input
      ~ mean(., na.rm = TRUE),
      .before = 100,
      .after = 100
    )
  )
vic_elec %>% 
  ggplot() +
  aes(x = Time) +
  geom_line(aes(y = Temperature), col = "grey") +
  geom_line(aes(y = temp_moving_avg_200), col = "red")

Task - add .complete = TRUE Only calculate for the window if there are the full amount of datapoints available.

vic_elec <- vic_elec %>% 
  mutate(
    temp_moving_avg_200 = slide_dbl(
      Temperature,
      # functional notation, with . standing for input
      ~ mean(., na.rm = TRUE),
      .before = 1000,
      .after = 1000,
      .complete = TRUE
    )
  )
vic_elec %>% 
  ggplot() +
  aes(x = Time) +
  geom_line(aes(y = Temperature), col = "grey") +
  geom_line(aes(y = temp_moving_avg_200), col = "red")
